{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"98d3c8e4-e851-4176-8b29-04f080b0cde2","content":"\n\nIn .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. You override `CreateWindow` in your `Application` class and use a custom `Window` subclass:\n\n```csharp\n// App.xaml.cs\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    return new MyWindow(new AppShell());\n}\n```\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()    // ← OnStart\n    {\n        base.OnCreated();\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnStopped()    // ← OnSleep\n    {\n        base.OnStopped();\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnResumed()    // ← OnResume\n    {\n        base.OnResumed();\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Mapping:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (`Window`) |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart` | `OnCreated` |\n| `OnSleep` | `OnStopped` |\n| `OnResume` | `OnResumed` |\n\nMAUI also adds `OnActivated`, `OnDeactivated`, `OnBackgrounding`, and `OnDestroying` for more granular control. If you need platform-specific hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5dcb603b-50e4-4ca1-8b7d-0f7e7faf6971","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` subclass. In .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`, or override the `CreateWindow` method and hook into `Window` events.\n\nActually, in .NET MAUI, the `Application` class still has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` — but they're not the recommended approach. The recommended approach is to use **Window lifecycle events**:\n\n\n- `Window.Created` maps to `OnStart`\n- `Window.Stopped` and `Window.Backgrounding` map to `OnSleep`\n- `Window.Resumed` maps to `OnResume`\n\nAlternatively, you can override `CreateWindow` to subscribe to window events directly, or use the `ILifecycleEventHandler` pattern for more granular control. Let me clarify though — the old `Application` lifecycle methods were actually removed in MAUI, so the Window-based approach is the way forward.","outputTokens":868},"id":"f378d760-2dfe-4ee3-9729-e86ab121a5dc","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:41:37.902Z","parentId":"b97b7ca0-98f0-4859-9fa8-63742fc0ba7b"}
